SIMPLE: many
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Many
<hw>Ma"ny</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Meine</er>,
<er>Mansion</er>.]</ety> <def>A retinue of servants; a household.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Many</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Many
<hw>Ma"ny</hw>, <pos>a. & pron.</pos> <note>[It has no variation to
express degrees of comparison; <xex>more</xex> and <xex>most</xex>,
which are used for the comparative and superlative degrees, are from a
different root.]</note> <ety>[OE. <ets>mani</ets>, <ets>moni</ets>, AS.
<ets>manig</ets>, <ets>m⟦ae⟧nig</ets>, <ets>monig</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>menig</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>manag</ets>, G. <ets>manch</ets>, Dan.
<ets>mange</ets>, Sw. <ets>m⟦aring⟧nge</ets>, Goth. <ets>manags</ets>,
OSlav. <ets>mnog'</ets>, Russ. <ets>mnogii</ets>; cf. Icel.
<ets>margr</ets>, Prov. E. <ets>mort</ets>. ⟦root⟧103.]</ety>
<def>Consisting of a great number; numerous; not few.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt be a father of <qex>many</qex> nations.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xvii. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Not <qex>many</qex> wise men after the flesh, not <qex>many</qex>
mighty, not <qex>many</qex> noble, are called.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. i.
26.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Many</xex> is freely prefixed to participles,
forming compounds which need no special explanation; as,
<xex>many-</xex>angled, <xex>many-</xex>celled, <xex>many-</xex>eyed,
<xex>many-</xex>footed, <xex>many-</xex>handed, <xex>many-</xex>leaved,
<xex>many-</xex>lettered, <xex>many-</xex>named,
<xex>many-</xex>peopled, <xex>many-</xex>petaled,
<xex>many-</xex>seeded, <xex>many-</xex>syllabled (polysyllabic),
<xex>many-</xex>tongued, <xex>many-</xex>voiced, <xex>many-</xex>wived,
and the like. In such usage it is equivalent to
<altname>multi</altname>. Comparison is often expressed by
<xex>many</xex> with <xex>as</xex> or <xex>so</xex>. ⟦ldquo⟧As
<xex>many</xex> as were willing hearted . . . brought bracelets.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Exod. xxxv. 22.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧So <xex>many</xex> laws argue so
<xex>many</xex> sins.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au> <xex>Many</xex> stands
with a singular substantive with <xex>a</xex> or
<xex>an</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Many a</b></col>, <cd>a large number taken
distributively; each one of many.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧For thy sake have I shed
<xex>many a</xex> tear.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Full <xex>many
a</xex> gem of purest ray serene.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Gray.</au> -- <col><b>Many
one</b></col>, <cd>many a one; many persons.</cd> <au>Bk. of Com.
Prayer.</au> -- <col><b>The many</b></col>, <cd>the majority; -- opposed
to <contr>the few</contr>. See <er>Many</er>, <pos>n.</pos></cd> --
<col><b>Too many</b></col>, <cd>too numerous; hence, too powerful;
<as>as, they are <ex>too many</ex> for us</as>.</cd>
<rj><au>L'Estrange.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Numerous; multiplied; frequent; manifold;
various; divers; sundry.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Many</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Many
<hw>Ma"ny</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>menigeo</ets>,
<ets>menigo</ets>, <ets>menio</ets>, multitude; akin to G.
<ets>menge</ets>, OHG. <ets>manag⟦imac⟧</ets>, <ets>menig⟦imac⟧</ets>,
Goth. <ets>managei</ets>. See <er>Many</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The populace; the common people; the majority of
people, or of a community.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After him the rascal <qex>many</qex> ran.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A large or considerable number.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>many</qex> of our bodies shall no doubt⟦br⟧
Find native graves.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Seeing a great <qex>many</qex> in rich gowns.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It will be concluded by <qex>many</qex> that he lived like an
honest man.</q> <rj><qau>Fielding.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense, <xex>many</xex> is connected immediately
with another substantive (without <xex>of</xex>) to show of what the
<xex>many</xex> consists; as, a good <xex>many</xex> [of] people think
so.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is liable to a great <qex>many</qex> inconveniences.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Many-minded</ent>⟦br⟧
